JOHANNESBURG Mineral Resources Minister Mosebenzi Zwane instructed the Minerals and Petroleum Board on Friday to verify whether Anglo Gold Ashanti took into consideration industry commitments to save jobs before it tannounced plans to retrench more than 8,000 workers.READ: Mining communities demand 5,000 jobs AngloGold Ashanti said on Wednesday it had started consulting with employees to retrench 8,500 workers at its South African operations, which employ about 28,000 people, including contractors.Zwane said the instruction to verify this information was to ensure that the proposed actions by Anglo Gold Ashanti took into account the commitments made in the declaration signed by industry stakeholders to save jobs.So it appears minister Zwane doesn't trust AngloGoldAshanti; asks DMR MP board to verify the data providedZwane met the chief executive of AngloGold Ashanti, Srinivasan Venkatakrishnan, and his executives on Friday. We continue to appeal to companies to act responsibly and with sensitivity.These are not just numbers to be thrown around, but people s livelihoods and future job prospects, and we should not take this matter lightly, Zwane said.READ: Mining industry 'opposed to SA's transformation'More information on the latest round of retrenchments is expected to be made available after the Commission for Conciliation, Mediation and Arbitration (CCMA) appoints a facilitator for the process in terms of the Labour Relations Act.Zwane reminded companies that the Section 52 process in terms of the Mineral and Petroleum Resources Development Act (MPRDA), and Section 189 process of the Labour Relations Act (LRA) should be adhered to in order to avoid the creation of uncertainty in the industry.Mineral Resources Minister instructed Minerals Board to verify Anglo Gold Ashanti's reasons to consider retrenching up to 8500 workers.Section 52 of the MPRDA states that the holder of mining rights remains responsible for the implementation of the processes provided in the LRA pertaining to the management of downscaling and retrenchment, until the minister of Mineral Resources has issued a closure certificate to the holder concerned.The silence of the save sa chairperson on the possible retrenchments of 8500 workers at anglo gold ashanti is not on.Anglo Gold Ashanti wants to place on care and maintenance the Kopanang mine in the Vaal River region, and the Savuka section of the TauTona mine, in the West Wits Region. Savuka has been in operation for 59 years and has already been extended 10 years beyond its natural life. Kopanang Mine produced its first gold in 1981, 36 years ago.African News Agency